hotspot.description:
Pictured here is the Nazareth Capability Wheel Diagram.
At Nazareth we teach specific lessons to support our students in their development of these capabilities. We believe these foster personal development for our learners in the areas of - Identity- Managing Self- Thinking & Questioning- Collaboration and Connecting & Reflecting.
hotspot.title: Nazareth Capabilities - Skills for Success

hotspot.description: Pictured here are the Bullying Awareness and Student Responsibility posters. Our Community purpose statement guides us as followers of Jesus. We are called to love one another. As teachers and educators at Nazareth it is our call to support students in their social and emotional development, and we aspire to teach our students how to interact with others in a meaningful and loving way, how to resolve conflict with one another and how to understand their own emotions and feelings as they grow and develop in our care.
hotspot.title: Student Responsibility

hotspot.description: Students in Year 5 receive a laptop device to take home. Families are involved in our annual Cyber Safety Evening which aims to teach both student and parent about responsibilities, risks and rewards of having their own device. Students begin to engage in online learning through our school platform SEQTA, receiving assignments and due dates electronically, submitting work online and learning important ICT skills that will support them in their learning journey.
hotspot.title: Student Laptops

hotspot.description: As leaders of our Findon Campus our Year 6 students have the opportunity to apply for a Captain position. Primary Captains are selected for each House group as well as each specialist area. These captains hold a special responsibility as role models to their fellow peers, acting as representatives of our community.
hotspot.title: Primary Captains

hotspot.description: Students are immersed in conversations in their learning at Nazareth around Positive Psychology. Teachers guide students through lessons on having a ‘Growth mindset’ and use the analogy of ‘The Learning Pit’ to support students in verbalising their understanding of how they learn and persevere through challenges. These lessons allow students to build resilience, empower them to use positive self-talk and they create a safe environment that welcomes and embraces mistakes as part of the learning process.
hotspot.title: Positive Psychology

hotspot.description: Students begin the transition to High School early in Semester two each year. These transitions involve visits to our Secondary Campus as well as students involved in a Mental Health & Wellbeing Day that focuses specifically on topics that are relevant and topical to them as they begin this move into a High school setting.
hotspot.title: Preparing for secondary schooling
